
00:00:00,300 --> 00:00:01,321
This is the shark tank,

00:00:01,321 --> 00:00:03,305
where hopeful entrepreneurs

00:00:03,305 --> 00:00:05,800
get a once-in-a-lifetime chance
to pitch the sharks

00:00:05,800 --> 00:00:07,802
in hopes of getting
an investment

00:00:07,802 --> 00:00:09,815
to start, grow, or save
their businesses.

00:00:09,815 --> 00:00:11,805
What's your sales
in the last month?

00:00:11,805 --> 00:00:14,792
Sales were $5,500.
That is nothing.

00:00:14,792 --> 00:00:16,805
The entrepreneurs must
convince a shark to invest

00:00:16,805 --> 00:00:18,800
the full amount
they're asking for,

00:00:18,800 --> 00:00:20,806
or they'll walk away
with nothing.

00:00:20,806 --> 00:00:21,810
Here's the truth.

00:00:21,810 --> 00:00:23,806
You don't have a business.
You have a hobby.

00:00:23,806 --> 00:00:25,806
If someone offered you
$3 million today,

00:00:25,806 --> 00:00:27,793
you wouldn't take it?
I wouldn't take it, Mark.

00:00:27,793 --> 00:00:28,793
You're a fool.
(Stammers) Mark, I--

00:00:28,793 --> 00:00:30,793
you're a fool. I'm out.

00:00:30,793 --> 00:00:32,813
If the sharks hear
a great idea...
Whoa!

00:00:32,813 --> 00:00:35,794
They're ready to invest,
using their own money.

00:00:35,794 --> 00:00:36,797
If you're gonna stay
on your path,

00:00:36,797 --> 00:00:39,795
you need a big wallet.
Happen to have one.

00:00:39,795 --> 00:00:40,818
And they're willing
to fight each other

00:00:40,818 --> 00:00:42,793
for a piece of the action.

00:00:42,793 --> 00:00:44,791
What is this?
Kevin, give the guy a break.

00:00:44,791 --> 00:00:45,811
This is business!
Are we gonna hold hands

00:00:45,811 --> 00:00:46,818
and sing "Kumbaya" here?

00:00:46,818 --> 00:00:48,793
Shut up, Kevin.

00:00:48,793 --> 00:00:49,796
♪♪

00:00:49,796 --> 00:00:50,802
Who are the sharks?

00:00:50,802 --> 00:00:52,792
They're self-made millionaire

00:00:52,792 --> 00:00:53,817
and billionaire investors

00:00:53,817 --> 00:00:56,790
who are entrepreneurs
themselves.

00:00:56,790 --> 00:00:57,800
♪♪

00:00:57,800 --> 00:01:00,790
Kevin O'Leary
is a venture capitalist

00:01:00,790 --> 00:01:03,797
who turned a $10,000 loan
into a software business

00:01:03,797 --> 00:01:06,794
worth $4.2 billion.

00:01:07,812 --> 00:01:09,811
Barbara Corcoran

00:01:09,811 --> 00:01:11,796
went from waiting tables
in Manhattan

00:01:11,796 --> 00:01:15,807
to building the city's
preeminent real estate empire.

00:01:15,807 --> 00:01:18,813
Robert Herjavec, the son
of an immigrant factory worker,

00:01:18,813 --> 00:01:20,807
is now a technology mogul

00:01:20,807 --> 00:01:22,805
who sold his first
Internet companies

00:01:22,805 --> 00:01:26,798
for over $350 million.

00:01:26,798 --> 00:01:28,810
Lori Greiner,
the queen of QVC,

00:01:28,810 --> 00:01:30,804
holds over a hundred patents

00:01:30,804 --> 00:01:32,811
and has launched
over 300 products,

00:01:32,811 --> 00:01:34,805
grossing over
a half a billion dollars

00:01:34,805 --> 00:01:36,805
in retail sales.

00:01:36,805 --> 00:01:37,817
And Mark Cuban,

00:01:37,817 --> 00:01:41,801
notorious billionaire
entrepreneur, tech guru,

00:01:41,801 --> 00:01:45,433
and the outspoken owner
of the NBA's Dallas MavEricks.

00:01:56,233 --> 00:02:00,229
First into the tank is a mom
from Highland Park, Illinois,

00:02:00,229 --> 00:02:04,212
with a product to make kids
feel more safe and secure.

00:02:04,212 --> 00:02:06,238
♪♪

00:02:14,567 --> 00:02:16,033
Hello, sharks.

00:02:16,033 --> 00:02:18,033
My name is Debbie Glickman,

00:02:18,033 --> 00:02:21,029
and my company
is Fairytale Wishes.

00:02:21,029 --> 00:02:24,400
I am asking for
a $35,000 investment

00:02:24,400 --> 00:02:27,402
in exchange for 33%
of my company.

00:02:27,402 --> 00:02:30,404
When my son
was a little boy,

00:02:30,404 --> 00:02:32,400
he was scared to go to sleep
at night.

00:02:32,400 --> 00:02:35,388
So I ended up buying
a teeny-weeny bottle

00:02:35,388 --> 00:02:37,407
of $25 lavender pillow spray,

00:02:37,407 --> 00:02:39,406
and I told my son
it was a magic potion

00:02:39,406 --> 00:02:42,386
that would give him
sweet dreams,

00:02:42,386 --> 00:02:45,387
and he bought it,
and he went right to sleep.

00:02:45,387 --> 00:02:47,383
And I thought to myself,

00:02:47,383 --> 00:02:48,410
you know what?
There's an idea there.

00:02:48,410 --> 00:02:53,400
Fairytale Wishes is a line
of magic aromatherapy sprays

00:02:53,400 --> 00:02:58,392
to help empower children
through the use of yummy scents

00:02:58,392 --> 00:02:59,406
and their imagination.

00:02:59,406 --> 00:03:04,381
A couple of sprays of
our signature lavender-scented

00:03:04,381 --> 00:03:07,395
sweet dreams spray
on your child's pillow...
(Spritzes)

00:03:07,395 --> 00:03:09,403
Will assure your child
sweet dreams

00:03:09,403 --> 00:03:11,406
are on the way.

00:03:11,406 --> 00:03:14,394
And if your kids have
monsters under the bed...
(Growl)

00:03:14,394 --> 00:03:15,408
(Laughter)

00:03:15,408 --> 00:03:19,393
Our bubblegum-scented
monster repellent

00:03:19,393 --> 00:03:22,384
will keep the monsters
far, far away,

00:03:22,384 --> 00:03:24,402
because in case
you didn't know it,

00:03:24,402 --> 00:03:27,867
monsters are terrified
of the smell of bubblegum.

00:03:27,867 --> 00:03:29,857
(Laughter)

00:03:29,857 --> 00:03:33,866
I have some sample pillows
for you.

00:03:33,866 --> 00:03:35,846
A pillow for everybody.
Thank you.

00:03:35,846 --> 00:03:36,854
You're welcome.
Oh, my favorite.

00:03:36,854 --> 00:03:39,865
Cotton candy scent.
Thank you, Debbie.

00:03:39,865 --> 00:03:42,863
Grape jelly scent. (Laughs)
Grape jelly.

00:03:42,863 --> 00:03:44,840
(Robert)
Wow, it smells really good.

00:03:44,840 --> 00:03:45,861
They smell good.
Thank you.

00:03:45,861 --> 00:03:47,845
I mean, that really smells
like bubblegum, grape jelly.

00:03:47,845 --> 00:03:48,861
What does it cost--what does
it cost you to make this?

00:03:48,861 --> 00:03:51,860
It costs $2.16 to make.
To make it?

00:03:51,860 --> 00:03:52,934
Yeah.
Why is it so expensive?

00:03:52,934 --> 00:03:55,940
Because--well, 'cause I make it
here in the United States, and--

00:03:55,940 --> 00:03:57,941
and what do you sell them for?
The 4-ounce bottle

00:03:57,941 --> 00:03:59,947
has been selling for $9.99.
How many have you sold

00:03:59,947 --> 00:04:04,931
over what period of time?
We have been in business
for four years, and last year,

00:04:04,931 --> 00:04:06,933
our sales were $5,500.

00:04:06,933 --> 00:04:07,949
$5,500?

00:04:07,949 --> 00:04:09,930
That is nothing.

00:04:11,953 --> 00:04:14,947
What I've learned is that
P.R. is really our key,

00:04:14,947 --> 00:04:17,929
because when we see P.R.--
you know what?

00:04:17,929 --> 00:04:18,942
I'm just telling you...
Uh-huh?

00:04:18,942 --> 00:04:21,940
To me, that is the ultimate
red--red flag.

00:04:21,940 --> 00:04:24,944
When somebody thinks
it's all about P.R.,

00:04:24,944 --> 00:04:26,933
"if I only got
on one more TV show,"

00:04:26,933 --> 00:04:28,933
"if I only got
in one more magazine"--

00:04:28,933 --> 00:04:30,926
you're always looking for
a-a shortcut.
Well, I'll tell you what.

00:04:30,926 --> 00:04:32,942
We did a 6-store test
with Bed Bath &amp; Beyond,

00:04:32,942 --> 00:04:36,932
and in one month,
they reordered three times.

00:04:36,932 --> 00:04:37,940
It was during the holidays.

00:04:37,940 --> 00:04:39,939
They had it up
in the front of the store.

00:04:39,939 --> 00:04:42,952
The minute they put it
in the back of the store,

00:04:42,952 --> 00:04:44,924
sales tanked.

00:04:44,924 --> 00:04:45,931
Welcome to the real world.

00:04:45,931 --> 00:04:46,943
If they didn't reorder,

00:04:46,943 --> 00:04:48,926
it's because it didn't make
enough money per linear foot

00:04:48,926 --> 00:04:49,936
for them to care about it.

00:04:49,936 --> 00:04:51,932
They put another product
in there that sold much better.

00:04:51,932 --> 00:04:53,935
Well, they--when they moved it
to the back of the store--

00:04:53,935 --> 00:04:56,934
but then what happened--
Bed Bath &amp; Beyond sees
a new Debbie every day...

00:04:56,934 --> 00:04:57,946
Right. Right.
With another product.

00:04:57,946 --> 00:04:59,946
The only Debbies that get
to stay in sell product.

00:04:59,946 --> 00:05:01,928
Yours didn't.
They threw you out.

00:05:01,928 --> 00:05:03,934
Here's the truth.

00:05:03,934 --> 00:05:05,923
You don't have a business.
You have a hobby.

00:05:05,923 --> 00:05:07,940
That's it. Take the rest
of the inventory.

00:05:07,940 --> 00:05:10,000
Put it under the bed.
Let the monster eat it,

00:05:10,000 --> 00:05:11,990
and forget about this one.
(Laughs)

00:05:11,990 --> 00:05:13,018
You know what?
In all due fairness...

00:05:13,018 --> 00:05:15,009
That was rude.
Thank you.

00:05:15,009 --> 00:05:17,667
I have never, ever gotten
anything

00:05:17,667 --> 00:05:20,675
but wonderful, positive
feedback.
No, but that's not true.

00:05:20,675 --> 00:05:22,677
Do you know why? Because
the best feedback in the world,

00:05:22,677 --> 00:05:26,669
the only feedback
you could trust is sales.

00:05:26,669 --> 00:05:29,654
Listen, I'm great at all
the creative stuff,

00:05:29,654 --> 00:05:31,662
and I'm not so great
at the business end,

00:05:31,662 --> 00:05:34,650
and that's why I came here
to find a partner

00:05:34,650 --> 00:05:36,652
to help me
with the business end.

00:05:36,652 --> 00:05:38,677
Debbie, I-I think you're
driving meshugge. Honestly.

00:05:38,677 --> 00:05:40,667
I don't think you have
a firm grasp

00:05:40,667 --> 00:05:42,653
on all the different pieces.

00:05:42,653 --> 00:05:43,677
You know, I have to jump in.
I don't agree with Mark.

00:05:46,676 --> 00:05:49,657
♪♪

00:05:51,649 --> 00:05:52,663
♪♪

00:05:52,663 --> 00:05:54,670
Debbie, I don't think
you have a firm grasp

00:05:54,670 --> 00:05:56,651
on all the different pieces.

00:05:56,651 --> 00:05:57,674
I have to jump in.
I don't agree with Mark.

00:05:57,674 --> 00:05:59,653
I think that this is
very creative.

00:05:59,653 --> 00:06:01,677
I think kids probably love it.

00:06:01,677 --> 00:06:03,678
I love your creativity
about this product.

00:06:03,678 --> 00:06:07,651
Nobody's gonna buy this.
Apparently nobody has bought it.
I think it may need some help.

00:06:07,651 --> 00:06:09,656
She's--she said herself,
she's not good at sales.

00:06:09,656 --> 00:06:11,657
Some of the monsters
you sprayed four years ago

00:06:11,657 --> 00:06:13,668
have died of old age, and you
still don't have any sales.

00:06:13,668 --> 00:06:15,669
(Laughter)

00:06:15,669 --> 00:06:17,934
You don't have a business.
I'm out.

00:06:17,934 --> 00:06:19,200
Don't you have kids, Kevin?

00:06:19,200 --> 00:06:21,204
Of course I do.
He eats his children.

00:06:21,204 --> 00:06:23,333
Look, I just tell 'em,
if there's any monsters around,

00:06:23,333 --> 00:06:25,322
I'll take care of it,
and they believe me.
(Laughs)

00:06:25,322 --> 00:06:26,533
Thank you, Barbara.

00:06:26,533 --> 00:06:28,540
It doesn't work on him.
I will tell you

00:06:28,540 --> 00:06:30,539
what I think would help you.
Okay.

00:06:30,539 --> 00:06:32,549
I don't think that
parents and families

00:06:32,549 --> 00:06:34,534
need this big of a bottle.

00:06:34,534 --> 00:06:37,529
I think if you made
a 5-pack...
Uh-huh.

00:06:37,529 --> 00:06:38,534
Of small bottles,

00:06:38,534 --> 00:06:39,546
then you have
your monster spray,

00:06:39,546 --> 00:06:41,536
the lavender spray...
The small bottle..

00:06:41,536 --> 00:06:43,537
Then you buy all 5
for like $7.99.
Are expensive to make.

00:06:43,537 --> 00:06:47,529
And then a mother has
something...
They're expensive to make,
though. Right.

00:06:47,529 --> 00:06:49,532
Well, you've gotta get
better sourcing.

00:06:49,532 --> 00:06:50,539
Right.
But to me,

00:06:50,539 --> 00:06:52,538
I just think
a different marketing strategy

00:06:52,538 --> 00:06:53,542
might be more helpful.

00:06:53,542 --> 00:06:55,544
Right, right.
I think having five flavors--

00:06:55,544 --> 00:06:57,535
I don't think is
at all necessary.

00:06:57,535 --> 00:06:59,529
You should have
one magic spray, period.

00:06:59,529 --> 00:07:02,531
Decide what it is.
Call it "magic spray."
Yeah.

00:07:02,531 --> 00:07:04,549
You could make a good product
of this. You're creative,

00:07:04,549 --> 00:07:06,541
but you know what?
It's not selling.

00:07:06,541 --> 00:07:08,545
So you gotta redo it
and figure out what to do

00:07:08,545 --> 00:07:11,543
and I don't wanna take
that ride with you. I'm out.

00:07:11,543 --> 00:07:14,526
Okay. Thank you so much.

00:07:15,554 --> 00:07:19,527
Here's an idea. Here's an idea
that maybe you'll like.

00:07:19,527 --> 00:07:22,555
So I came up with this idea
to partner with Disney, okay?

00:07:22,555 --> 00:07:28,526
Disney has
25,000 hotel rooms...

00:07:28,526 --> 00:07:30,538
Debbie, have you called Disney?
In the U.S.

00:07:30,538 --> 00:07:31,541
Not yet.

00:07:31,541 --> 00:07:33,527
(Laughter)
But I'm gonna.

00:07:33,527 --> 00:07:35,538
I-I need someone to help
guide me through that end of it.

00:07:35,538 --> 00:07:38,550
You know what I'm--
do you know what I'm saying?
(Robert) Oh, come on, Debbie.

00:07:38,550 --> 00:07:41,539
Right.
You've got it
into Bed Bath &amp; Beyond,

00:07:41,539 --> 00:07:43,539
so don't tell me you couldn't
pick up the phone

00:07:43,539 --> 00:07:46,538
and call the other ones,
because you did it once.
Right. No, no, no.
I understand, so--

00:07:46,538 --> 00:07:47,553
a goal--Debbie, a goal
is great to have.

00:07:47,553 --> 00:07:49,546
Right.
But you gotta have a timeline.

00:07:49,546 --> 00:07:53,533
A goal without a timeline
is simply a dream.

00:07:53,533 --> 00:07:55,537
Right.
I'm out.

00:07:55,537 --> 00:07:57,527
Okay, thank you.

00:07:59,531 --> 00:08:01,551
Mark?

00:08:01,551 --> 00:08:03,540
Debbie, Debbie, Debbie.

00:08:03,540 --> 00:08:05,532
Listen, here's the thing.

00:08:05,532 --> 00:08:07,528
I will do anything
in my power

00:08:07,528 --> 00:08:09,542
