00:29:14,557 --> 00:29:16,569
Take a cup,
put some water in it,

00:29:16,569 --> 00:29:18,569
you stick it in the microwave,

00:29:18,569 --> 00:29:21,563
your pour the noodles in,
you eat it, you go to sleep,

00:29:21,563 --> 00:29:23,558
you wake up, recover
from your hangover.

00:29:23,558 --> 00:29:25,556
(Laughs)
I've been making it
in the microwave all my life.

00:29:25,556 --> 00:29:27,559
Put you never get
the stovetop quality taste.

00:29:27,559 --> 00:29:30,568
Sometimes--
you're drunk.
It doesn't matter.

00:29:30,568 --> 00:29:32,545
It does.
It does matter.

00:29:32,545 --> 00:29:35,541
Other bowls just heat
excess water.

00:29:35,541 --> 00:29:37,564
And they're not specifically
designed to cook ramen noodles.

00:29:37,564 --> 00:29:40,551
Help me out here.
You got a $300,000 ask,

00:29:40,551 --> 00:29:44,541
and I get 10%
of the rapid ramen cooker.

00:29:44,541 --> 00:29:49,542
So computed value's
3 million bucks.
Correct.

00:29:49,542 --> 00:29:51,551
Now before I put you
in the microwave...
(Laughs)

00:29:51,551 --> 00:29:53,549
Explain to me
why that makes sense.

00:29:53,549 --> 00:29:55,568
Tell me about your sales
and how much cash you've made.
Absolutely.

00:29:55,568 --> 00:29:57,548
In the last three months,

00:29:57,548 --> 00:29:59,560
I've done over $164,000
in sales.

00:29:59,560 --> 00:30:02,567
Wow.
How much do you sell
the rapid ramen cooker for?

00:30:02,567 --> 00:30:04,569
Uh, it retails for $5.99.

00:30:04,569 --> 00:30:06,569
(Kevin) Okay, and how much
does it cost to make?

00:30:06,569 --> 00:30:09,547
About 75 cents.
And it's all online?

00:30:09,547 --> 00:30:11,549
You don't have any retailers
selling this?

00:30:11,549 --> 00:30:12,556
Absolutely incorrect.

00:30:12,556 --> 00:30:14,565
We went from zero stores
to over 2,500 stores

00:30:14,565 --> 00:30:16,544
in the last three months.

00:30:16,544 --> 00:30:17,554
Who are the stores?

00:30:17,554 --> 00:30:20,543
We are in Raley's,
Albertsons, Safeway,

00:30:20,543 --> 00:30:22,555
Winco, H-E-B in Texas.

00:30:22,555 --> 00:30:24,548
(Robert) How did you get into
all those stores?

00:30:24,548 --> 00:30:26,566
Grinding, man. I just
pick up the phone and call.

00:30:26,566 --> 00:30:28,549
Good for you.
I love that.

00:30:28,549 --> 00:30:30,562
Chris, is that all you?
Every single, uh, retailer

00:30:30,562 --> 00:30:32,569
that I've, uh, landed
was all me.

00:30:32,569 --> 00:30:35,555
If this keeps going, why can't
somebody just knock this off?

00:30:35,555 --> 00:30:37,558
It's patent pending.
What's patented?

00:30:37,558 --> 00:30:38,567
It's the reservoir design

00:30:38,567 --> 00:30:41,541
of a container that cooks
ramen noodles.

00:30:41,541 --> 00:30:44,542
You seem very bright
and very enterprising to me.

00:30:44,542 --> 00:30:46,558
I'd like to hear
about your background.

00:30:46,558 --> 00:30:49,559
Well, I've been an entrepreneur
since I was 16 years old.

00:30:49,559 --> 00:30:52,133
At 16, there was nothing
to do for teenagers,

00:30:52,133 --> 00:30:54,138
so I created dance parties.

00:30:54,138 --> 00:30:57,142
Charging 10 bucks a head,
I was making $4,000

00:30:57,142 --> 00:30:59,141
in just one event.
At 19 years old,

00:30:59,141 --> 00:31:01,123
I had
my own modeling agency.

00:31:01,123 --> 00:31:02,137
When I got out of college,

00:31:02,137 --> 00:31:04,137
I started
my own staffing company.

00:31:04,137 --> 00:31:07,129
Uh, with zero revenue,
did over a million dollars

00:31:07,129 --> 00:31:08,138
in less than 14 months.

00:31:08,138 --> 00:31:09,142
What happened to that business?

00:31:09,142 --> 00:31:11,119
That business
is still rolling.

00:31:11,119 --> 00:31:12,142
Do you own it?

00:31:12,142 --> 00:31:14,125
I still own 100%
of that business.
You still running it?

00:31:14,125 --> 00:31:17,131
Well, what I did is
I hired my long-term employee,

00:31:17,131 --> 00:31:19,143
uh, to run the day-to-day
operations of that company,

00:31:19,143 --> 00:31:22,138
and I've been focusing 100%
on rapid ramen.

00:31:22,138 --> 00:31:25,121
To me, that suggests

00:31:25,121 --> 00:31:27,139
that all you've done
is jump from

00:31:27,139 --> 00:31:29,132
quickie business
to quickie business

00:31:29,132 --> 00:31:31,115
to quickie business,

00:31:31,115 --> 00:31:33,128
because either you lose interest
or you can't run the business.

00:31:33,128 --> 00:31:35,139
Absolutely not, Mark.
With the staffing company,

00:31:35,139 --> 00:31:38,115
when we hit this recession,

00:31:38,115 --> 00:31:39,122
uh, it was the biggest hit

00:31:39,122 --> 00:31:41,116
my--I've ever experienced
in my life.

00:31:41,116 --> 00:31:42,143
Fair enough.
Look, I feel your pain, right?

00:31:42,143 --> 00:31:44,139
Everybody got hit.
Continued to happen.

00:31:44,139 --> 00:31:46,131
Uh, staffing company
has not recovered.

00:31:46,131 --> 00:31:49,143
But what I understood is that I
could not part-time this thing.

00:31:49,143 --> 00:31:52,118
I had
a huge opportunity here,

00:31:52,118 --> 00:31:54,126
so I put all my focus
on rapid ramen.

00:31:54,126 --> 00:31:57,116
What's your sales
in the last month?
About $80,000.

00:31:57,116 --> 00:31:59,135
And what percentage of that
was through retailers?

00:31:59,135 --> 00:32:00,144
About 80% is retail.

00:32:00,144 --> 00:32:03,118
My projections
with just safeway alone--

00:32:03,118 --> 00:32:04,143
you know,
just selling one a day.

00:32:04,143 --> 00:32:07,122
Right now in winco,
we're selling three a day,

00:32:07,122 --> 00:32:09,132
21 units a week.
You are?

00:32:09,132 --> 00:32:11,130
What does that look like
for the whole year?

00:32:11,130 --> 00:32:12,141
For the whole year,
we're--we're expected

00:32:12,141 --> 00:32:15,115
to do over $2 million
this year.

00:32:16,127 --> 00:32:18,115
Okay, so something's
not adding up here.
It doesn't compute.

00:32:18,115 --> 00:32:19,135
Yeah, I'm having a problem, too.

00:32:19,135 --> 00:32:23,125
If you're doing $80,000 a month
with huge margins,

00:32:23,125 --> 00:32:24,139
you should be generating,
you know,

00:32:24,139 --> 00:32:26,142
very quickly $300,000
in cash flow

00:32:26,142 --> 00:32:28,122
to reinvest in the business.

00:32:28,122 --> 00:32:32,115
Right now I have over $150,000
in receivables.

00:32:32,115 --> 00:32:34,132
But I look
at our bank account.

00:32:34,132 --> 00:32:36,136
It's--we're just
turning through the pro--

00:32:36,136 --> 00:32:37,140
through our inventory.

00:32:37,140 --> 00:32:39,117
So you need capital
for inventory.

00:32:39,117 --> 00:32:40,122
We need capital
for inventory.

00:32:40,122 --> 00:32:42,118
You need $300,000 right now?

00:32:42,118 --> 00:32:43,124
Based on our projection,

00:32:43,124 --> 00:32:44,135
we may even need
a little more than that,

00:32:44,135 --> 00:32:46,117
but I-I take it off
the $300,000

00:32:46,117 --> 00:32:49,115
because I do have receivables
coming in.

00:32:49,115 --> 00:32:51,133
So your expectation is
if I give you $300,000 today

00:32:51,133 --> 00:32:55,139
and you need another million
tomorrow, I'm gonna fund that?

00:32:55,139 --> 00:32:57,124
I hope you have the wherewithal
to do that.

00:32:58,126 --> 00:33:00,135
I think what happens here is
you wanna run with this thing,

00:33:00,135 --> 00:33:03,117
sell as many as you can
till you burn it out.

00:33:03,117 --> 00:33:04,121
That's basically it.
Well, that's not--

00:33:04,121 --> 00:33:05,130
because there
will be competitors

00:33:05,130 --> 00:33:06,132
that come in at a lower price

00:33:06,132 --> 00:33:08,118
and squeeze that margin
down to pennies.

00:33:08,118 --> 00:33:09,143
There's nothing proprietary
about this.

00:33:09,143 --> 00:33:11,119
I understand you have a patent,

00:33:11,119 --> 00:33:12,123
but a small modification
will do the same thing.

00:33:12,123 --> 00:33:13,130
You understand that.

00:33:13,130 --> 00:33:14,131
Which leads to the question,

00:33:14,131 --> 00:33:15,141
how did you get
to your valuation?

00:33:15,141 --> 00:33:17,142
We're gonna do $2 million
this year.
You hope.

00:33:17,142 --> 00:33:19,133
Yeah, it's hard to see--
I don't hope, mark.

00:33:19,133 --> 00:33:21,119
(Kevin) Well,
of course he hopes.
I'm--I'm--yeah.

00:33:21,119 --> 00:33:23,124
You hope, just like when
you had your staffing business.

00:33:23,124 --> 00:33:24,126
I'm sure things were great,

00:33:24,126 --> 00:33:25,144
and you projected out
a whole lot more.

00:33:25,144 --> 00:33:27,140
Just like when you had
your model business.

00:33:27,140 --> 00:33:29,133
What you're really saying is
your business is worth

00:33:29,133 --> 00:33:33,122
$3 million
on what, $200,000 in sales?

00:33:33,122 --> 00:33:34,135
Well, I'll tell you this.

00:33:34,135 --> 00:33:37,121
If I were offered $3 million
today to sell the company,

00:33:37,121 --> 00:33:38,124
I wouldn't sell it,

00:33:38,124 --> 00:33:39,136
based on the growth
that we're having.

00:33:39,136 --> 00:33:42,132
If someone offered you
$3 million today,

00:33:42,132 --> 00:33:44,118
you wouldn't take it?

00:33:44,118 --> 00:33:45,134
I wouldn't take it, Mark.

00:33:45,134 --> 00:33:47,144
Un-un-undeniably,
I wouldn't take it.

00:33:47,144 --> 00:33:49,129
You're a fool.
You're a fool.
I wish I had the courage.

00:33:49,129 --> 00:33:50,134
Mark, I--
you're a fool. I'm out.

00:33:52,124 --> 00:33:54,137
I don't know
if I like your plan

00:33:54,137 --> 00:33:57,136
to burn up all my cash
in inventory.

00:33:57,136 --> 00:34:00,137
'Cause one day, what happens
to products like this is,

00:34:00,137 --> 00:34:01,141
they stop selling.

00:34:01,141 --> 00:34:03,135
And whatever's sitting
in the warehouse,

00:34:03,135 --> 00:34:05,128
you own it,
and you gotta eat it.

00:34:05,128 --> 00:34:07,116
If you're gonna stay
on your path,

00:34:07,116 --> 00:34:09,144
you need a big wallet.
Happen to have one.

00:34:09,144 --> 00:34:11,132
(Chuckles)
All right?

00:34:11,132 --> 00:34:13,121
So here's an offer
I'll make for you, okay?

00:34:13,121 --> 00:34:15,129
I think it may be
the only offer you get.

00:34:15,129 --> 00:34:17,140
I will give you your $300,000.

00:34:17,140 --> 00:34:20,127
I want $1.10...

00:34:20,127 --> 00:34:23,118
Ha!
Every time you sell one
until I get my cash back,

00:34:23,118 --> 00:34:25,119
because I don't know
how long it's gonna take you

00:34:25,119 --> 00:34:26,142
to sell 300,000 units.

00:34:26,142 --> 00:34:28,144
And after I get my cash back,

00:34:28,144 --> 00:34:31,143
I get 50 cents in perpetuity.

00:34:31,143 --> 00:34:34,117
Chris, this product's gonna last
about two years, maybe three.

00:34:34,117 --> 00:34:36,135
What equity are you taking?
Zero equity.

00:34:36,135 --> 00:34:39,117
I don't want any equity.
That is a real offer,

00:34:39,117 --> 00:34:40,126
and I think that actually

00:34:40,126 --> 00:34:42,122
encapsulates the risk
I've got here.

00:34:42,122 --> 00:34:43,143
I need to get
this capital back

00:34:43,143 --> 00:34:47,128
before this little fad ends,
my friend. That's--
I'll tell you, I think

00:34:47,128 --> 00:34:49,135
even for you, back when
you were eating in college,

00:34:49,135 --> 00:34:52,120
they ate ramen noodles,
and so--
hey, I ate ramen noodles.

00:34:52,120 --> 00:34:53,128
I get it.
Yeah.

00:34:53,128 --> 00:34:55,120
But I didn't need to spend
5 bucks to get this bowl.

00:34:55,120 --> 00:34:56,124
I figured it out on my own.

00:34:56,124 --> 00:34:59,133
Well, I think
that you are fantastic.

00:34:59,133 --> 00:35:03,137
I personally am concerned about
somebody else trying to do this.

00:35:03,137 --> 00:35:06,126
That's one of my worries
for you.

00:35:06,126 --> 00:35:10,117
So I'm not going to
personally invest.

00:35:10,117 --> 00:35:11,129
I'm sorry. I'm out.

00:35:11,129 --> 00:35:13,137
I--thank--
I appreciate you.

00:35:13,137 --> 00:35:16,141
Chris, I tasted this,
fully expecting it to be mushy,

00:35:16,141 --> 00:35:19,128
because I have tried
to save three minutes

00:35:19,128 --> 00:35:21,118
on many occasions in
sticking it in the microwave,

00:35:21,118 --> 00:35:22,130
and it doesn't work.

00:35:22,130 --> 00:35:26,142
This tastes exactly the same
as if I cooked it on the stove.

00:35:26,142 --> 00:35:30,130
But I'm not totally sold this is
gonna make you a ton of money.

00:35:30,130 --> 00:35:32,135
It's a onetime sale.

00:35:32,135 --> 00:35:35,125
I feel badly saying "no" to you
because I like you a lot.

00:35:35,125 --> 00:35:37,138
I feel like Lori, for God sakes.
"I like you a lot."

00:35:37,138 --> 00:35:39,138
(Laughs)
But I'm out.

00:35:43,117 --> 00:35:46,129
Chris, I love the story
how you got here.

00:35:46,129 --> 00:35:48,123
I love the fact you did it
on your own.

00:35:48,123 --> 00:35:50,144
A guy offered to buy my company
for $5 million.

00:35:50,144 --> 00:35:52,126
I thought it was all the money
in the world.

00:35:52,126 --> 00:35:54,137
I came home. I told my wife
I'm taking the offer.

00:35:54,137 --> 00:35:56,133
I had the papers,
and my wife said, "why?

00:35:56,133 --> 00:35:58,116
You don't believe in yourself
enough?"

00:35:58,116 --> 00:36:00,119
I turned the offer down

00:36:00,119 --> 00:36:03,126
because my wife believed in me
more than I believed in myself.

00:36:03,126 --> 00:36:06,121
I'm gonna start crying.
And a few years later,
I sold it for $100 million.

00:36:06,121 --> 00:36:09,118
Chris,
my only issue with this is

00:36:09,118 --> 00:36:10,143
I can't get over the value
of the business today--

00:36:10,143 --> 00:36:13,144
Robert, are we gonna hold hands
and sing "Kumbaya" here?
$300,000. The business

00:36:13,144 --> 00:36:17,128
is not worth $3 million.
Shut up, Kevin.
What is this?

00:36:17,128 --> 00:36:18,140
The business is not worth
$3 million today.

00:36:18,140 --> 00:36:20,124
Help me get there.

00:36:20,124 --> 00:36:21,139
♪ Kumbaya ♪
Oh, stop it.

00:36:21,139 --> 00:36:23,123
♪ Kumbaya ♪

00:36:23,123 --> 00:36:25,131
Kevin, give the guy
a break.

00:36:25,131 --> 00:36:26,143
This is business!
Get to it!

00:36:26,143 --> 00:36:28,119
I know. Take it seriously here.
This is business.

00:36:28,119 --> 00:36:29,141
This is the guy's life.
This is his life.

00:36:29,141 --> 00:36:32,143
Give him a chance.
Every store that I've contacted,
I've been able to get in,

00:36:32,143 --> 00:36:35,115
and they're selling,
and they're moving product.

00:36:37,120 --> 00:36:39,135
Chris, I wanna be in business
with you.

00:36:39,135 --> 00:36:42,135
Here's what I'm comfortable
with today.

00:36:42,135 --> 00:36:45,122
I'll give you the $300,000
for 40%.

00:36:45,122 --> 00:36:48,128
Wow.
That's giving you
a pretty good value

00:36:48,128 --> 00:36:51,138
for a new company, and really,
I'm taking you at your word

00:36:51,138 --> 00:36:53,137
because I think you're gonna
make it happen.

00:36:55,135 --> 00:36:57,135
So you have two offers now.

00:36:57,135 --> 00:36:59,132
You've succeeded where many
other people have not

00:36:59,132 --> 00:37:00,141
in "Shark Tank."

00:37:02,121 --> 00:37:03,134
What are you going to do?

00:37:03,134 --> 00:37:07,116
♪♪

00:37:10,122 --> 00:37:12,119
Three sharks are out,

00:37:12,119 --> 00:37:14,124
but Chris has two offers--

00:37:14,124 --> 00:37:18,433
$300,000 for a royalty
of $1.10 per unit,

00:37:18,433 --> 00:37:20,467
which drops to 50 cents

00:37:20,467 --> 00:37:23,489
once the investment
is paid back to Kevin.

00:37:23,489 --> 00:37:26,484
And $300,000 for 40% equity
from Robert.

00:37:26,484 --> 00:37:28,485
So you have two offers now.

00:37:28,485 --> 00:37:32,476
Uh, if you don't mind, I'd like
to make a call and, uh--

00:37:32,476 --> 00:37:33,496
you understand the nuances
